In any case, when Pecham succeeded Kilwardby in the archiepiscopate of Canterbury, he followed resolutely in the footsteps of his predecessor, and with trenchant letters to the Chancellor and doctors of Oxford and even to the Bishop of Lincoln he made every effort to prevent the rehabili- tation of the propositions condemned in 1277.

These letters inserted in Pecham’s Register‚ published by Wilkins and more correctly by Martin, were re-edited in 1889 by Father Ehrle in the Zeitsclerift fiir Kathol. T lieologie, xiii. 172-193. In the first letter addressed, Ioth November, 1284, dilectis filiis cancellario et magistris ac scholaribus universitatis oxoniensis, he says he has noticed with sorrow that some persons in the University of Oxford still continue to hold opiniones quas- dam erroneas quas recolendae memoriae dominus Robertus . . . dignoscitur condemnasse.
